SPECIES COMMENTS: About the size of Red-winged Blackbirds though none were nearby for comparison. One bird was primarily all dark with a pale whitish eye
OBSERVER ID: while the other was more of a lighter medium to coal gray with a whitish eye. I originally thought that they were Brewer's Blackbirds but
FIRST NAME: when I got a closer look
LAST NAME: especially the lighter bird had nice dark orange edges to the tertials and a few of the greater coverts. However
SAMPLING EVENT IDENTIFIER: these did not contrast highly with the rest of the wing. Additionally it had darker lores and a hint of the usually striking facial pattern of females in winter plumage. (Frankly
PROTOCOL TYPE: I'm a little surprised by this plumage at this time of year and would have assumed that they were early to late spring birds rather than January birds.) No vocalizations. They were perched in salt cedars above water at first. Later saw them hopping among low branches and to the ground in grass at water's edge on an island.

SPECIES COMMENTS: I observed the species in the company of Rosemary English who owned the English Ranch at that time.  The riparian woodland along White River at that location and at that time had a closed canopy and in the winter was marsh-like due to the high water table. That is the ground was wet with extensive
OBSERVER ID: but very shallow pools of standing water.  Mrs. English had observed Rusty Blackbirds at that location during several previous winters
LAST NAME: and she invited me to see them.----I noted the blackbirds the size and shape of Brewer's with a similar pale iris
SAMPLING EVENT IDENTIFIER: but differing in the extensive rust-brown feather edgings
PROTOCOL TYPE: more pronounced in the females.  I don't have record of the number that were present
DURATION MINUTES: probably fewer than 10.  I also don't have a memory of whether or not other observers from the Llano Estacado Audubon Society were present or not.

Female mallard appeared to have some sort of problem with its right leg. Grackles aplenty and some redwings on the eastern bay shore. Heard a long series of hey sweeties from chickadee(s). Yesterday I saw a Red-bellied try the log on the road oak, but it appeared startled and flew off again when the log moved as it landed on it. TRIP COMMENTS: Very warm (80''s). Windy. A junco-less day.
Nice day
FIRST NAME: really. Cleaned up litter and junk from woods and roadsides
SAMPLING EVENT IDENTIFIER: what a dump. First turtles of the year sunning in the pond! ----Saw redtail (with red tail) circling several times. Only a couple Tree Swallows early
PROTOCOL TYPE: including one investigating pipe-pole in the pond (as a nest cavity?). More showed up early evening
PROJECT CODE: flying high over the house. Female mallard (noticed yesterday) definitely has an injury or abnormality of right leg or toe - saw her again on land right by goose nest on the point (nesting geese are totally OK with mallards and wood ducks
DURATION MINUTES: apparently). Possible meadowlark in the field early evening (heard). Blue Jay showed up quite late
EFFORT DISTANCE KM: announced itself. Don''''t know if it got a peanut or not
EFFORT AREA HA: since I''''m sure it saw me outside. 2 egrets flying together into pond. Kingisher''''s rattle heard this morning
NUMBER OBSERVERS: saw it eating something it caught. Disappeared not long after
ALL SPECIES REPORTED: then heard it once late. Great Blue flew far away north when I went up on the roof
GROUP IDENTIFIER: then I saw one not too long after without seeing it fly back. Maybe there were two. 3 robins in the meadow at dusk. Noticed one possible first year bird (breast different) again. Saw the Killdeer flying over. Song Sparrows very late in the courtyard again - 7:40! Saw Pale Hairy at far oak cage and also hickory log. Geese still squablling away on island. Hard to tell if there are really any nests there or not. Saw a white egg-like object laying untended on the ground in what seems vaguely like a nest depression - laid and abandoned? Saw a goose on the island shore laying down and gathering leaves around her - practicing nest building? Found a pile of feathers under junk golf cart body in woods. Scared something away when I was cleaning up the east woods. Saw pair flying away from underneath
APPROVED: harsh call given - pair of sapsuckers
REVIEWED: maybe? Shape seems to fit. Saw at least 2 redwings that I can''''t tell about
REASON: whether they''''re females or 1st-year birds. Look too dark for females. Saw a chickadee drinking at the water tray. Lots of fee-beeing going on lately.

column44: but it must have slipped away. Found crow wing (right one
column45: this time) while I was snooping in the hedge.----BJUE JAY: Appreared late in the day for peanuts. Only one at feeder
column46: but 2 flew away.----MOURNING DOVE: Have noticed what seems to be a male running after a female on the ground lately. ----SONG SPARROW: Active in the brushpile
column47: late appearance again in courtyard.----AMERICAN ROBIN: On the lawn a couple times for a change. Still mostly unseen and unheard except for morning and evening.----HAIRY WOODPECKER: Saw Bright and Pale. Bright was on hickory log
column48: Pale on main oak peanuts.----RED-BELLIED WOODPECKER: Easily spooked by my presence in the yard
column49: wanted to come down for peanuts but wouldn''t until I left.----WHITE-BREASTED NUTHATCH: Not for the first time
column50: observed getting safflower seed in elm feeder.----RUSTY BLACKBIRD: Heard
column51: can''t say whether seen. It doesn''t seem as though they come to the feeders. Try as I do to spot them there
column52: it always turns out to be a female grackle.----EUROPEAN STARLING: Annoying me by knocking down sunflower seed with its useless poking.----GREAT EGRET: Neat sight when both it and Great Blue flew into view from the east
column53: egret turning off this way (couldn''t find it later)
column54: heron heading for its throne.----GREAT BLUE HERON: Only seen flying over a couple times until evening when it perched. ----BLUE-WINGED TEAL: If a female was among the group of 3
column55: her head at the very least looked different to me this time------------

SPECIES COMMENTS: from Hwy. 1 up Cross Creek about ½ mile. 1030-1115. Clear
FIRST NAME: The Rusty Blackbirds have been here for over a week. The female seemed to be typical. The male appeared to be in-between fall plumage and breeding plumage. Its feathers were mostly dark (black) with a rusty patch on the back and rusty tips to the breast feathers. The eye line was strong. The female had a light eye. Both birds were together and feeding in the creek. They would walk along in the water turning over leaves and other debris in search for food. We observed them for about 5 minutes and then they flew upstream. There were several Brewer¿s Blackbirds in the area so we were able to get good looks at them for comparison. The male Brewer¿s were very obvious in their iridescence with purple tones to their heads whereas the Rusty male showed no iridescence at all. There was no hint of an eye stripe or mustache on the Brewer¿s; the Rusty showed both a strong eye stripe and mustache stripe. Brewer¿s females have dark eyes
LAST NAME: this Rusty female had light eyes. The female Rusty appeared grayer than female Brewers with a good strong gray rump. The female Brewer¿s were a warm brown underneath with a grayish rump but not as pronounced as the female Rustys.

TRIP COMMENTS: This was a fun day
FIRST NAME: but still quite nice. Matt and I picked up another person I hadn''t met before
LAST NAME: and we headed off to do some birding a Smithville. I thinkwe went in hope of  seeing the 3 species of Loon that were reported at that time
SAMPLING EVENT IDENTIFIER: but we only saw a couple of commons. The highlights occured at the sparrow spot
PROTOCOL TYPE: where we picked up two male Purple Finch
PROJECT CODE: and a large flock of Rusty Blackbirds! Which were life birds for me
DURATION MINUTES: though I suppose I had seen them before at Perry? Anyhow
EFFORT AREA HA: we were even able to get a nice comparison between them and a few Common Grackles that were hanging out. My notes on the Rusty Blackbirds
NUMBER OBSERVERS: aside from the fact that they were sort of moving along through the underbrush as we moved forward is that they are pretty cool looking birds. There were about 30 of them
ALL SPECIES REPORTED: both male and female. They were hanging out in the company of grackles and robins. The males have a brown body with blackish brown wings. The breast is slightly mottled with black specles. It had a brighter rufus cap and a dark beak that seemed to make the face a little black. The eyes are bright yellow. It also appeared to have a weak supercillium. The tail is squared off. The female is pretty too
GROUP IDENTIFIER: similar but is mostly brown all over. Very cool birds!!!! However
APPROVED: the second goody of the day wansn''t to be found until reaching my computer back home....

This birdtrip covered most of the roads northwest to southwest of Sparta
FIRST NAME: from Fanchers Mills to Quebeck on the west to Sparta and Rt. 1/70S on the east.----Winston A. Walden accompanied me on this trip.  Weather began cloudy but turned mostly sunny with not too much wind (Beaufort 0-2 most of the time) and with temps in the 30s and low 40s.----The Redheads were scattered on many ponds
LAST NAME: most of which were high due to recent heavy rains in Tennessee (up to five inches fell in the three days preceding this trip).  Many fields were wet or covered with wet-weather ponds.----The Northern Harrier was a female or immature hunting the large field north of the intersection of Old Smithville Hwy. and Lizard Lane.----The Ring-billed Gulls were at or near Boiling Pond on Pete Felton Rd.----The Loggerhead Shrike was found on Eaton Rd.; it was photographed impaling a grub on a barbed wire fence
SAMPLING EVENT IDENTIFIER: possibly a display for the purpose of securing a mate.----The Orange-crowned Warbler was seen extremely well at 15-20 feet on Jericho Rd. Its yellow undertail coverts were distinctly seen
PROJECT CODE: blurry streaking on its breast.  Otherwise it was a plain yellow-green warbler with no distinguishing features.----The Palm Warbler was seen several times over the course of 30 minutes while we were working a stubble field near the same site as the NOHA was seen.  One of three pipit observations occurred at this site
DURATION MINUTES: too.----The Chipping Sparrows were at two sites; this has been a very good winter for them in the Upper Cumberland Region.----Rusty Blackbirds were encountered in small numbers at about 5 sites within the area we birded.
